han just pure mind—rather, it signifies a mind directly connected to the body: the human being that I am. Understood in this new light, the Descartes Marion uncovers through close readings of works such as Passions of the Soul resists prominent criticisms leveled at him by twentieth-century figures like Husserl and Heidegger, and even anticipates the non-dualistic, phenomenological concepts of human being discussed today. This is a momentous book that no serious historian of philosophy will be able to ignore.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMind and bodyxPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy17th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aDescartes.  aSixth Meditation.  abody.  aflesh.  aonto-theo-logy.  apassive thought.  asenses.  aunion.1 aGschwandtner, Christina M.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106885800 cprintz978022619258140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226192611423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226192611/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles